<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="554" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="554">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,367,393]" pageId="3" pageNumber="554">Remarks</emphasis>
. Forewing venation of this species is very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wei &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2010" box="[975,1173,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Yaontogonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="554" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="darjeelingensis">
<emphasis box="[975,1173,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="554">Y. darjeelingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but the forewing coloration is different including having only one yellow triangular spot compared to at least two in the other two species and also it has a much wider and swollen clypellus compared to the other two species with the laterofrontal sutures obscure above the antennal bases, while in other species extended dorsally close to the eye. The male genitalia are a little different from 
<taxonomicName box="[395,537,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Yaontogonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="554" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavopicta">
<emphasis box="[395,411,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="554">Y</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[425,537,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="554">flavopicta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(male unknown for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wei &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2010" box="[767,965,511,537]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Yaontogonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="554" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="darjeelingensis">
<emphasis box="[767,965,511,537]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="554">Y. darjeelingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) but there is similarity in the shape of the subgenital plate with medial placement of macrosetae.
</paragraph>
